    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_740232792" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/740232792" />
    <a title="Elizabeth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2455537-elizabeth"><img alt="Elizabeth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1402467471p2/2455537.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/740232792?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth" href="/user/show/2455537-elizabeth">Elizabeth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2455537-elizabeth?shelf=medieval-renaissance">medieval-renaissance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer740232792" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17586811934587380381">More like a 2.5 for me. I was tempted to give this three stars, and then realized I&apos;d read the very ending of the story wrong, so I&apos;m pretty comfortable with the two-star rating. <br/><br/>The thing is, I did end up warming up to this novel, but there is so much of it that wasn&apos;t as well executed as it could have been. I can&apos;t really say that I liked it, but it does get pretty compelling <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[once Kate ends up in the realm of the Fairy Folk <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, that I couldn&apos;t put it down (amusingly</span>
  <span id="freeText17586811934587380381" style="display:none">More like a 2.5 for me. I was tempted to give this three stars, and then realized I'd read the very ending of the story wrong, so I'm pretty comfortable with the two-star rating. <br /><br />The thing is, I did end up warming up to this novel, but there is so much of it that wasn't as well executed as it could have been. I can't really say that I liked it, but it does get pretty compelling <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[once Kate ends up in the realm of the Fairy Folk <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, that I couldn't put it down (amusingly, right after the point I declared the book incredibly boring and yet decided to keep going anyway). <br /><br />I agree with a couple of reviews I've seen that say that the pacing of this novel is seriously wonky. The beginning of the book is intensely boring. If you can get past the first 70 or so pages of the book, then you've got over the worst of it, but that's a decent chunk of the novel so you have to ask yourself whether it's worth it. Then the plot really gets going and everything is happening at once, and then boom, roll out the ending credits. <br /><br />I also agree with those who say the climax is anti-climactic. I thought "... wait, that's it?" I was a bit disappointed. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[How do you have an adaptation of Tam Lin and nothing/no one transforms?! I guess it makes sense because the Fairy Folk in this are strongly implied to be human. Except then there's that thing at the end with the Guardian of the Well, which goes unexplained, plus then the Lady disappears between her and Kate's last interaction with each other. Whatever it is, a climax that's solved largely by talking does not an exciting climax make <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />However, I did really like <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[the part when Kate is taken prisoner by the Fairy Folk. It was all very properly strange and eerie. I loved the idea of the weight, as well. In general I thought the Fairy Folk part of the book had some great world-building (if it can be called that), although I can understand the criticism that it felt underdeveloped. But still, I liked it a lot <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />Oh, and I also agree (so much agreement going on) with those reviewers who say that the historical setting feels arbitrary. It appears to me that Pope chose the Tudor time period because she wanted the book to be set in the past, and was most familiar with the Tudors, so she just went with it. There's no real reason why the book is set during this time, it just is. I guess it's not the worst sin of the book, but it does feel a little lazy, and as with a lot of historical fiction where the setting isn't very well-defined to the plot or the characters, the result is that you don't get a very good sense of time and place. The book could have been set any time after the introduction of Christianity to the British isles which, obviously, is a lot of lee-way. <br /><br />About the romance......oh boy. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Who doesn't like witty banter between two romantic leads? And I can be honest and say I love brooding hero-types. But Christopher Heron is kind of an asshole and it felt at times that Pope didn't really know how to balance his character. He's an asshole but he's also self-sacrificing but he's also got a heart of gold underneath it all ... However, the amount of gravitas needed to ground his character and give him a sense of nobility was pretty much all but absent. He spends most of the novel being exasperated at Kate, or telling her what to do, and none of that read as very romantic to me. I get why they might be attracted to each other--both are intellectual equals, both are going through being imprisoned by the Fairy Folk--but Pope dilutes so much of the romantic tension between them that it just kind of reads as a lot of tension instead.<br /><br />And then there are times when Christopher sounds rather controlling in a sinister way, when he says things like "I'd save the trouble of your husband beating you" (something like that) or how he might have to use the double locks on a door to lock Kate in (towards the end, aka right before he proposes to her). Um... am I supposed to find this funny? It sounds messed up, especially since we know they're supposed to end up together.<br /><br />At the same time, Christopher does clearly care for Kate and at one point calls her his "best friend" which Kate doesn't seem to notice, and her obliviousness to her relationship with Christopher is kind of hilarious. <br /><br />When I said up above that I read the ending wrong, I thought what had happened was that the Lady may or may not have enchanted Christopher into loving Kate, to the point that she would wonder for the rest of her life whether or not he actually loved her or just chose her because he was influenced to. But then I realized, that was what the Lady was trying to do, and not what she actually did. In general, I liked the novel's take that the mind is a powerful thing, and being able to influence it could be considered a sort of magic. Once I remembered that Kate is a skeptic about the magic, the ending became clearer. <br /><br />But where am I going with this... ah, right. Since this is the case, and the novel does end on an unequivocal Happily Ever After..... seriously? This is the romantic proposal I was waiting for? He doesn't even ask her, he just tells her they're going to get married! How is that romantic? And he gets her consent by asking her, "What more do you want?" and she replies, "Nothing", when the word "nothing" has a pretty chilling connotation for the both of them. I get understated romances, and for the longest time the book did a great job of depicting that, but when it comes to the Happily Ever After, I don't know, I felt the execution could've been a lot better. He doesn't even tell her he loves her, for heaven's sake. He just goes on about how she's such a part of him that he didn't think to tell her that. Well, good for you, but how the heck is the poor girl supposed to know if you don't outright tell her?! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I don't regret reading this book because it had been on my to-be-read list for the longest time, but I probably wouldn't ever read this again and I can't say I really recommend it. There are some good parts here and there, but you have to wade through a lot of boring exposition to get to it, and then the ending wasn't as well executed as I'd hoped it would be. However, if you're a huge fan of the Tam Lin ballad and are always up for a Tam Lin retelling, you'd probably get more out of this than I did, so read away. But that's pretty much the one instance I'd recommend the book to anyone. If you're not this type of person, I'd say you could probably comfortably skip this one.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17586811934587380381" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


